<span id="freeTextContainer7364680523984696773">I need reminders from time to time, like those in this novel, of psychological and moral atrocities, of the hyper-viciousness of a pack lead by unstable maniacs and sociopaths. <br/><br/><u>Darkness at Noon</u> is a chilling novel about Nicholas Salmanovitch Rubashov, an old Bolshevik, formerly Commissar of the People, and a leader in the 1917 Russian REVolution, who is imprisoned during Stalin&apos;s purges after he speaks out against the tyranny of his former comrades. These former comrades torture Rubashov and bre</span>
  <span id="freeText7364680523984696773" style="display:none">I need reminders from time to time, like those in this novel, of psychological and moral atrocities, of the hyper-viciousness of a pack lead by unstable maniacs and sociopaths. <br /><br /><u>Darkness at Noon</u> is a chilling novel about Nicholas Salmanovitch Rubashov, an old Bolshevik, formerly Commissar of the People, and a leader in the 1917 Russian REVolution, who is imprisoned during Stalin's purges after he speaks out against the tyranny of his former comrades. These former comrades torture Rubashov and break him psychologically until he confesses to "crimes" he did not commit. <br /><br />A powerful political classic.<br /></span>
