<div id="review_3609512129" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3609512129" />
    <a title="Debbie Zapata" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22110057-debbie-zapata"><img alt="Debbie Zapata" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451631863p2/22110057.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3609512129?book_show_action=true">Oct 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Debbie Zapata" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Debbie Zapata" href="/user/show/22110057-debbie-zapata">Debbie Zapata</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/3320200-darkness-at-noon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22110057-debbie-zapata?shelf=2020printbooks">2020printbooks</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3609512129" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7918857010582065889">Oct 29, 1pm ~~ Review asap.<br/><br/>Oct 30, 1158pm ~~ I wish I had written down where I saw this book mentioned. I know it was in an article about authoritarian states, but beyond that, I&apos;m blank. I just remember that I thought it would be something almost vital to read during this bizarre year we are all trying to get through. <br/><br/>Author Arthur Koestler was Hungarian born but was raised in Austria, where he joined the Communist Party in 1931. But in 1938 he resigned because he did not agree with the way the</span>
  <span id="freeText7918857010582065889" style="display:none">Oct 29, 1pm ~~ Review asap.<br /><br />Oct 30, 1158pm ~~ I wish I had written down where I saw this book mentioned. I know it was in an article about authoritarian states, but beyond that, I'm blank. I just remember that I thought it would be something almost vital to read during this bizarre year we are all trying to get through. <br /><br />Author Arthur Koestler was Hungarian born but was raised in Austria, where he joined the Communist Party in 1931. But in 1938 he resigned because he did not agree with the way the Party was changing under the leadership of Joseph Stalin. He published this book in 1940 and my translated edition came out in 1941. (The GR blurb for my edition is a near duplicate of what is written on the inside flap of the cover. Here is the missing final sentence: "Recent history has provided corroborating testimony to his fictional critique of the ruthlessness of modern revolutionary procedures.")<br /><br />Darkness At Noon is the story of Rubashov, who, when we meet him, is entering a prison cell. He had been high up in the Party, one of the old guard of original revolutionaries. But now times have changed, the Party is evolving under its new boss, known only as No. 1, but clearly meant to be Stalin. Rubashov is an intellectual and therefore suspect, and the story follows the efforts of the prison officials to have him admit that he is now a bad influence and a major liability. We also share in Rubashov's meditations about his role in the Party and the Party's role in the world.<br /><br />Sometimes in these mental wanderings I got a bit lost. Philosophy is never an easy-peasy topic whether it is in a text book or a novel. But through it all, I became attached to Rubashov and felt almost as though I was pacing that little cell myself, tapping on the walls in code to send messages to my neighbors, and drumming on the door when a prisoner is dragged down the corridor to the stairs that lead to the room where executions are held.<br /><br />This is an intense book, not always easy to completely understand, but it will certainly make the reader think. One of the thoughts I had while reading was this: has the world ever seen a pure version of Communism? I mean the way Marx himself imagined it? Seems to me that once an '-ism' goes out from paper into the world it is altered by whichever leader happens to be in power. Lenin developed his version, then Stalin added his brand to the mix. <br /><br />All plans work perfectly on paper, but I wonder if a pure Marxist Communism would really be any better than the kind the world saw being forced upon people? And come to think of it, if a way of life is forced upon people, how can it ever be a real success? Even though it may be hard to believe in 2020, most people will not always behave like hypnotized sheep. Eventually they begin to think for themselves and discover that life is not unfolding the way they were told it would. And there the country sits, ripe for another revolution. Seems like an endless vicious circle, doesn't it. <br /><br />At the beginning of his interrogation process, Rubashov is interviewed by a man who used to be a compatriot but had now shifted himself to the new thinking in the Party. I liked what Rubashov told him: <b>"In those days we made history ~~ now you make politics."</b> Seems to me that politics has been the world's problem since....oh, I don't know....forever? <br /><br />Rubashov works out many issues for himself during his time in prison, and one of the most chilling arguments he makes to himself is this one: <b>He who opposes a dictatorship must accept civil war as a means. He who recoils from civil war must give up opposition and accept the dictatorship.</b> <br /><br />I wonder how many people in the world will face this dilemma during my lifetime? And since I am considering this little mental exercise, I wonder how I would react if <i>my</i> country lurched its way into autocracy? I know I am not very obedient, my husband teases me about that all the time. So I don't think I would flourish living under such a system. <br /><br />I also know I am Zapata, maybe only by marriage and not blood, but I am still quite proud of the name and what it stands for. Besides, how would I ever be able to face the spirit of Great-grandfather Emiliano if I didn't live up to our principles? <br /><br />Well, anyway. Enough exercising for one night. It's late and I need a little chocolate and a lot of sleep.<br /><br />I wholeheartedly recommend this book. As a matter of fact, the author has two others in which he explores the topic of rebellion. From the reviews I've seen they are not as compelling as this one, but I have ordered them anyway because I am curious to see how he approaches the idea when he is not using his own life as a broad outline for his plot. <br /><br />Just one more thing. In my little mental exercise, what would <i>you</i> do?<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7918857010582065889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


