  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4507794198" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4507794198" />
    <a title="Brian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1111042-brian"><img alt="Brian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567183757p2/1111042.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4507794198?book_show_action=true">Feb 01, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian" href="/user/show/1111042-brian">Brian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781416540267" href="/book/show/30673.Darkness_at_Noon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=public-library">public-library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=book-group-mens">book-group-mens</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=russia">russia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1111042-brian?shelf=translated">translated</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4507794198" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2137680024492250125"><em>Darkness at Noon</em> is a harrowing fictional portrayal of the moral bankruptcy of totalitarian political systems. Although the totalitarian state in question is not specifically named, it is clear that it is the U.S.S.R. and that the Party leader, referred to as “No. 1,” is Joseph Stalin. The novel is set in the late 1930s, when Stalin has succeeded in consolidating his power through mass arrests, show trials, and executions. <br/><br/>The novel’s protagonist, Nicolas Salmanovitch Rubashov, was a leader of t</span>
  <span id="freeText2137680024492250125" style="display:none"><em>Darkness at Noon</em> is a harrowing fictional portrayal of the moral bankruptcy of totalitarian political systems. Although the totalitarian state in question is not specifically named, it is clear that it is the U.S.S.R. and that the Party leader, referred to as “No. 1,” is Joseph Stalin. The novel is set in the late 1930s, when Stalin has succeeded in consolidating his power through mass arrests, show trials, and executions. <br /><br />The novel’s protagonist, Nicolas Salmanovitch Rubashov, was a leader of the Revolution and has been a faithful Party official for decades. But now, like so many of his contemporaries among the Party leadership, he has fallen out of favor with No. 1. The novel opens with his arrest and accompanies him through lonely days and nights in his cell and through multiple interrogations designed to elicit a confession, until his ordeal culminates in a trial.<br /><br />In prison, Rubashov reflects on his experiences in the Movement and the Party that he has served for almost his entire life. He knows that the only moral criterion that he and his comrades recognized is social utility—the ends justify the means, and any individual can be sacrificed for the movement. He is under no illusions about what is happening to him or why, or about what his likely fate will be. <br /><br />“For the movement was without scruples; she rolled towards her goal unconcernedly and deposed the corpses of the drowned in the windings of her course.… The motives of the individual did not matter to her. His conscience did not matter to her, neither did she care what went on in his head and his heart. The Party knew only one crime: to swerve from the course laid out; and only one punishment: death. Death … was the logical solution to political divergences.”<br /><br />Koestler is unsparing in his indictment of this dark totalitarian system. Through Rubashov’s reflections and philosophical musings, Koestler gives us an intimate inside look at this dystopian world, and it’s hard to come away without shuddering. Although <em>Darkness at Noon</em> is a novel, it provides a vivid description of a world that was—and in some places still is—all too real. The book is definitely worth reading and thinking about.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2137680024492250125" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

